Judge Mandisa Maya is South Africa’s very first female president of the Supreme Court of Appeal. She is under consideration for the position of Chief Justice. eNCA's Heidi Giokos reports. Courtesy of #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - It’s round two of interviews to find a new Chief Justice and on Wednesday the only female candidate is in the hot seat. Born in 1964 in rural Eastern Cape, Judge Mandisa Maya is a trailblazer. WATCH: Chief Justice Interviews | Who will don the robes? Not only is she South Africa’s very first female president of the Supreme Court of Appeal, she’s also the first black woman ever to be appointed to that court. If she takes over from Mogoeng Mogoeng, Maya will be the country’s first female Chief Justice. Maya’s other debuts include writing the first superior court judgment in isiXhosa in 2020.